    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A confidentiality period, or a \"confidentiality period,\" is a specific timeframe, like a set number of years, during which the parties agree to keep certain information secret.  In contrast, a survival clause dictates which parts of the contract *continue* to be legally binding even after the main agreement has ended. Think of it this way: the main contract might expire, but the obligations under a survival clause—like keeping secrets or paying off a debt—keep going strong. It's a safety net, ensuring some crucial rules stick around long after the initial deal is done.",
      "source": "target",
