    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. I'm actually looking at a specific section right now regarding \"indemnification\" and \"third-party claims.\" It's a bit dense. Could you explain what it actually means for my personal liability if I have to indemnify them? Like, what are the actual risks?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Indemnification, when you agree to indemnify someone, essentially means you promise to cover their losses if a third party sues them because of something you did or something related to your actions under the contract. If a third party comes after them, you step in and pay their legal bills and any damages they have to pay out. The risk to you is that you become the financial backstop for their potential messes, which can be quite substantial. It's a big commitment, making you responsible for their legal troubles stemming from your involvement.",
      "source": "target",
